Name: *cuyi-
Comment: See also [Proto-Chuukic](LanguageTable#cldf:protochuukic) _*cúyicúyi_ ‘yard, boom (of canoe)’. Note that this example, along with [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *mʷotu, mʷotu-Si ‘cut, sever, break off’, shows that pre [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*ns_ merged with Pre Proto-Oceanic _*nd_ and _*nt_ as [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) _*d_, contrary to present reconstructions for [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic) ([Grace 1969](Sources#cldf:grace1969), [Ross 1988](Sources#cldf:ross1988)). For further discussion and examples, see [Goodenough 1992 fn. 6](Sources#cldf:goodenough1992), [Goodenough 1997](Sources#cldf:goodenough1997).

Description: Gloss(html=tie, bind, refs=[], markdown='tie, bind', lookup='tiebind', comment='')
Name: *fau, fau-Si
Comment: Although it might appear that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _pawpéw_ ‘bind, tie’, _pawi-t_ ‘bind something’ and [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _pɨp_ ‘bind’, _pʷi_ ‘bind (something) could be loans from a Polynesian source such as [Samoan](LanguageTable#cldf:samoan) _faufau_ ‘bind’, the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) pairs _yawyéw/pawpéw_ and their transitives _yawi-t/pawi-t_ have the marks of ancient doublets, with the reduplicated pair exhibiting an _a/é_ alternation, something not found in Polynesian, but expected in [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) *_CaCu_ or *_CaCi_ reduplication, and also found in [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) ([Bender 1973](Sources#cldf:bender1973)). Other _y/p_ doublets in _Mrs_ include _yewyew_ ‘stroke, caress’, _pewpew_ ‘sweep, brush off’ and _yir_ ‘deviate’, _pir_ ‘slip down’. These doublets point to an origin as oral/nasal grade alternants (_*p/mp_) in [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:protooceanic). [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:kosraean) _ayʌ/pɨp_ and _awi/pʷi_ could have this same origin ([Bender 1973:463](Sources#cldf:bender1973)). See also [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *fatu, fatufatu‘to weave, plait’.

Name: *kai-peti

Description: Gloss(html=sky, heaven, storm, refs=[], markdown='sky, heaven, storm', lookup='skyheavenstorm', comment='')
Name: *laŋi
Comment: See also [Marck (1994:308)](Sources#cldf:marck1994) [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) _*laŋi_. In some languages (e.g., [Saipan Carolinian](LanguageTable#cldf:saipancarolinian), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese)), ‘bad weather’ meanings are to be found primarily in derived forms. Note that [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) _ḷaŋi-(n)_ has contrastive heavy _ḷ_ where light _l_ would be expected, with _i_ in next syllable, whereas heavy _ḷ_ is to be expected in the _ḷaŋe-(n)_ of a popular saying. Why the second vowel of this latter form is lowered in not understood, but it provides an explanation for the heavy _ḷ_s in the [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) ‘bad weather’ forms.

The [Marshallese](LanguageTable#cldf:marshallese) form reflects _*malakolako_; use of _-ló/-la_ directional with [Puluwatese](LanguageTable#cldf:puluwatese), [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:pohnpeian), and [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:mokilese) forms suggests that this is contamination of earlier _*maleku-lako_ (see [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *lako, laa ‘go, proceed, [as directional] away’). See also [Proto–Central Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protocentralmicronesian) *maluoki, maluoka ‘forget’, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:protomicronesian) *ma-lie ‘forget’.

Description: palm toddy
Name: kacii
Comment: Chk á instead of e suggests the possibility of a loan from Wol (palm toddy was known but not ordinarily made in Chuuk). Toddy making was probably introduced from the Philippines into the Western Carolinian atolls and thence spread to Chuuk and Yap. The Mrs terms jedan and jekaréw are loans from Kir te-ran (‘liquid’) and te-karewe (‘sweet or unfermented [coconut sap]’), Kir having developed its own distinct vocabulary for toddy making (see Bender 1981). See also PCk *cii, cii-ri ‘drip, sprinkle’, on which root this may be a causative construction.
